# **Overview** {#overview}

Phoenix Security’s REST API is the primary form of integration between customer’s systems and the platform. The API allows organizations to interact with their data and processes inside of Phoenix Security.

This document contains a detailed definition of the API flows and endpoints. In particular, it covers:

* Authentication: How do you authenticate clients against the API?  
* Managing Assets: list, create, and update any type of asset in the platform.  
* Managing vulnerabilities: Create and update lists of vulnerabilities and their details.

Over time the API endpoint coverage will expand to cover areas like Users, Teams, etc.

# **Authentication** {#authentication}

Access to the Phoenix Security REST API is controlled by API Client ID and Secret. However, requests to the API endpoints are not individually authenticated by those credentials. Instead, clients must use their ID and Secret to obtain time-limited access tokens \- then they can use the access token to authenticate each API request.

## **Client ID and Secret** {#client-id-and-secret}

Customers can generate one or more sets of API credentials in the Phoenix Security platform (Organisation \> API Access). Each of those sets can be managed independently so that potentially compromised credentials can be deactivated or removed from the platform.

![A screenshot of a computerDescription automatically generated][image1]

API Credential Management Phoenix Security

When users create API credentials in the UI they will only be able to see and copy the API Secret at the time of creation. This secret is stored in an encrypted form and can’t be decrypted again. It’s important that users copy and safely store the secret at the time of creation.

![A screenshot of a computerDescription automatically generated][image2]

API Credential Generation Phoenix Security

The Client ID is a “username” that allows for identification of the secret that needs to be checked \- it can be stored in clear text for easy lookup. The Client Secret should be stored in an encrypted (hashed) format so that it’s not possible to decrypt it but it’s possible to check if a clear text string matches the encrypted secret \- like it works with password storage and check.

## **Base URL** {#base-url}

The endpoint details in this document only include the API endpoint paths, without the base domain. The Phoenix Security base URL for SaaS production is [**https://api.securityphoenix.cloud**](https://api.securityphoenix.cloud).

For non production/demo  [https://api.demo.appsecphx.io/](https://api.demo2.appsecphx.io/) and [https://api.poc1.appsecphx.io](https://api.poc1.appsecphx.io) for enterprise PoC.

If you have a dedicated Enterprise deployment with its own URL in the form https://**mycompany**.securityphoenix.cloud your API domain would be https://**api.mycompany**.securityphoenix.cloud

If you are using any other environment, please check with Support for the correct base URL.

## **Obtaining Access Tokens** {#obtaining-access-tokens}

Before clients can make requests to the API they need to obtain an Access Token. In order to do so, clients need to send a request to the tokens endpoint and include an HTTP Basic Auth header with the Client ID (username) and Secret (password).

**GET /v1/auth/access\_token**

Headers:

`Authorization: Basic <client ID and secret>`

 

### **Responses**

Incorrect credentials: **401 Unauthorized**

Correct credentials: **200 OK**

`{`  
  `"token": string,`  
  `"expiry": number // Time of token expiration as Unix timestamp`

`}`

 

* **token**: An opaque (Bearer) token to be included in subsequent requests to the API.  
* **expiry**: The time of expiration of the token in [Unix timestamp](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix_time) format. Due to server time shift, clients should not rely on this timestamp alone, and should handle “token invalid or expired” responses as appropriate.

## **Using Access Tokens** {#using-access-tokens}

**All requests** to the Phoenix Security API \- except for the */v1/access\_token* endpoint \- should **include an access token** as part of the request. This is done through an Authorization/Bearer HTTP header.

`Authorization: Bearer <access token>`

If the token is missing, it’s incorrect or it has expired, the request would return an **401 Unauthorized** code. The response body might, or might not, contain additional details.

**API Response Codes**

Requests to the API will receive a response with one of the following status codes.

| Status Code | Verbs | Meaning | Suggested Action |
| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |
| 200 OK | GET | The request succeeded and the response body contains the result of the request in JSON format. | You can use the results of the request. |
| 201 Created | POST, PUT? | The new item was created successfully. |   |
| 204 No Content | DELETE | The item was successfully deleted; the response doesn't contain any further information. |   |
| 401 Unauthorized | All | The access token sent with the request is wrong or has expired. | Obtain a new access token and retry the request. |
| 404 Not Found | GET | The items accessed by the request doesn’t exist \- or the API credentials don’t have access to it. | If the item ID was returned by another API endpoint, contact support with details. |
| 500 Internal Error | All | There was a problem executing your request. This is a rare response and should not happen normally; however, clients should be ready to handle it. | The problem might be transient or permanent. Clients are advised **not** to retry indefinitely. |
| 503 Service Unavailable | All | This error means that the API service is not reachable at this point in time, but it’s likely to become available shortly. | Clients are advised to retry, for a limited number of times, if that suits their flow. |

# **Asset Management Endpoints** {#asset-management-endpoints}

This group of endpoints allow you to access the assets registry in order to query, insert and update assets.

## **Asset List** {#asset-list}

In order to obtain the asset list you can use the following request:

**POST /v1/assets**

### **Query Parameters**

Request page parameters:

`?pageNumber=0&pageSize=20`

Requests parameters are sent in the POST body.

`{`  
	`"requests": [`  
		`"type": "string",`  
		`"applicationEnvironmentId": "string (UUID)",`  
		`"componentServiceId": "string (UUID)",`  
		`"onlyUnassigned": true | false`  
		`"filters": [{`  
			`"key": "string",`  
			`"locality": ["string""],`  
			`"tagKeys": ["string""],`  
			`"tagValues": ["string],`  
			`// CLOUD ===============`  
			`"resourceType": ["string""],`  
			`"providerAccountId": ["string"],`  
			`"vpc": ["string"],`  
			`"subnet": ["string"],`  
			`"region": ["string"]`  
			`// INFRA =========`  
			`"cidr": "string",`  
			`"hostnames": ["string"],`  
			`"osNames": ["string"],`  
			`"netbios": ["string"],`  
			`"macAddress": ["string"]`  
			`//WEB/API ============`  
			`"cidr": "string",`  
			`"fqdn": ["string"]`  
			`// SAST/SCA/Container ===`  
			`"repository": ["string"],`  
			`"build": ["string"],`  
			`"dockerfile": ["string"],`  
			`"scannerSource": ["string"]`  
		`}]`  
	`]`  
`}`

where:

* **type** the type of assets to return; empty or missing means *any type.* Required.  
* **applicationEnvironmentId** is the Phoenix ID for the Application or Environment to return assets from. Optional.  
* **componentServiceId** is the Phoenix ID for the Component (App) or Service (Env) to return assets from; if this value is present “applicationEnvironmentId” will be ignored. Optional.  
* **onlyUnassigned** can be used to fetch only assets that are not assigned to any Environment (*true*), i.e. they are assigned to a Default Environment. If missing it defaults to *false* (include all).  Optional.

### **Response**

A successful request would return a JSON document with the following format:

`{`  
  `"content": [`  
    `{`  
      `"id": "string (UUID)",`  
      `"key": "string",`  
      `"type": "string",`  
      `"resourceType": "string",`  
      `"locality": "string",`  
      `"data": [`  
        `{`  
          `"source": "string",`  
          `"attributes": {`  
            `"<key>": "value",`  
          `}`  
        `}`  
      `],`  
      `"tags": [`  
         `"key": "string",`  
         `"value": "string"`  
      `]`  
    `}`  
  `],`  
  `"first": "boolean",`  
  `"last": "boolean",`  
  `"pageNumber": "number",`  
  `"pageNumberOfElements": "number",`  
  `"pageSize": "number",`  
  `"totalElements": "number",`  
  `"totalPages": "number"`  
`}`

## **Get Asset** {#get-asset}

In order to obtain the details of an asset you can use the following request:

**GET /v1/assets/\<asset-id\>**

### **Path Parameters**

* **asset-id**: This is the internal ID of the asset, as returned in the “id” field of the asset list request’s response.

### **Response**

A successful request would return a JSON document with the following format:

`{`  
      `"id": "string (UUID)",`  
      `"key": "string",`  
      `"type": "string",`  
      `"resource_type": "string",`  
      `"locality": "string"`  
      `"data": [`   
          `"source": "string",`  
          `"attributes": {`  
             `<attr_name> : <attr_value>`  
          `}`  
      `]`  
      `"tags": [`  
          `"key": "string",`  
          `"value": "string"`  
      `]`

`}`

 

Here `<attr_name>` and `<attr_value>` are placeholders for the different number and type of attributes that each **type of asset** contains.

## **Add Tags to Assets** {#add-tags-to-assets}

Tags can be added to assets using the following requests to either add them to a single asset or to multiple assets, respectively.

**PUT /v1/assets/\<asset-id\>/tags**

**PUT /v1/assets/tags**

### **Path Parameters**

* **asset-id**: This is the internal ID of the asset, as returned in the “id” field of the asset list request’s response.

### **Parameters**

Requests parameters are sent in the PUT body:

`{`  
   `"tags":[`  
      `{`  
         `"key":"string",`  
         `"value":"string"`  
      `}`  
   `],`  
   `"assetIds":["uuid"]`  
`}`

where:

* **tags\[\]**: Array of objects. A `key` is optional, `value` is required  
* **assetIds\[\]**: Array of UUID strings. Required in the version of the endpoint without the *\<asset-id\>* in the path; otherwise ignored. The list of asset IDs that the tags will be added to.

### 

### **Query Parameters**

`?pageNumber=0&pageSize=20`

Requests parameters are sent in the POST body.

`{`  
	`"applicationEnvironmentId": "string (UUID)",`  
	`"componentServiceId": "string (UUID)",`  
	`"assetId": "string (UUID)",`

	`"dateTo": "date"`  
	`"severityScoreFrom": "string",`  
	`"severityScoreTo": "string",`  
	`"cves": ["string"],`  
	`"epssScoreFrom": "string",`  
	`"epssScoreTo": "string",`  
	`"workflowTicketStatuses": ["string"],`  
	`"slaBreach": "string",`  
	`"workflowTicketSlaBreach": "string",`  
	`"tagKeys": ["string"],`  
	`"tagValues": ["string"],`  
	`"tagCategories": ["string"]`  
`}`

 

where:

* **applicationEnvironmentId** is the Phoenix ID for the Application or Environment to return vulnerabilities from

* **epssScoreTo** Allowed values: `0.0 - 1.0`

* **tagKeys** Allowed values: array of `[string]`  
* **tagValues** Allowed values: array of `[string]`  
* **tagCategories** Used to narrow down the search by **tagKeys/tagValues**. Allowed values: array of `[TECH_STACK, ALERT, COMPLIANCE, BUSINESS_UNIT, GENERAL]`

  `"last": "boolean",`  
  `"pageNumber": "number",`  
  `"pageNumberOfElements": "number",`

# **Import Endpoints** {#import-endpoints}

The import endpoints provide similar functionality to the Assessment Import area in the platform UI, but with a developer-friendly JSON format.

## **Import Assets** {#import-assets}

In order to import assets and vulnerabilities into Phoenix you can use the following endpoint:

**POST /v1/import/assets**

### **Parameters**

`{`  
  `"importType": "new" | "merge" | “delta”,`  
  `"assessment": {`  
    `"assetType": "string",`  
    `"name": "string"?,`  
  `},`  
  `"assets": [`  
    `{`  
      `"id": "string (UUID)",`  
      `"attributes": // Attributes objects (see list of required attributes)`  
      `"tags": Tag[],`  
      `"installedSoftware": InstalledSoftware[]`  
      `"findings": [`  
        `// See list of findings fields`  
      `]`  
    `}`  
  `]`  
`}`

where:

* **importType**: can be either “new”,  “merge” or “delta”  
* **assessment.assetType**: see table below for “Asset Type”'s  
* **assessment.name**: The name for a new assessment (when “id” is null)  
* **assets\[\].attributes**: List of asset details See table below for list of allowed fields for each type of asset.  
* **assets\[\].findgins\[\]**: List of findings within each asset. See table below for list of allowed fields for each type of asset.

**delta**: The import contains information about vulnerabilities and assets that are present in the system at this moment. However, it might not include all the vulnerabilities in each asset, and might not include all the assets in the scope of the assessment. The platform will add or update assets and vulnerabilities, but **will not remove or alter** any assets or vulnerabilities not present in the report.

**new, merge**: The report includes all the vulnerabilities currently present in all the assets in the scope of the assessment. If an asset or vulnerability (that was present in a previous report for this assessment) is not present in the new report the platform assumes that those vulnerabilities have been addressed, and will close them. Assets and vulnerabilities present in the new report will be created or updated as required. “*new*” imports remove existing vulnerabilities from the assets before importing; “*merge*” update as required.  
(**IMPORTANT**: Importing a delta report as a *new/merge* report **will close vulnerabilities** that might not have been intended to be closed by the user.)

### **Asset Attributes Fields**

All fields are **strings** unless indicated otherwise.

| Asset Type | Required fields | Optional fields |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| INFRA | **ip, hostname**   | **network, fqdn, os, netbios, macAddress** |
| WEB | **ip, fqdn** (one of the two) | **ip, fqdn** (one of the two) |
| CLOUD | **providerType**: “AWS”, “AZURE”, “GCP” **providerAccountId**: e.g. AWS ARN **region**: only required for Azure’ otherwise optional | **vpc, subnet, region** (for AWS, GCP) **providerAccountName**: user-friendly name **providerResourceId**: native resource ID from cloud provider **resourceGroup**: if available from the cloud provider |
| CONTAINER REPOSITORY CODE BUILD | **repository**: required for Repo **buildFile**: required for Build **dockerfile**: required for Container **scannerSource**: required for Code (JAR file, ZIP file, Snyk project,...) | **origin**: e.g. “github”   |

### 

### 

### **Findings Fields**

All fields are strings unless indicated otherwise.

| Required fields | Optional fields |
| ----- | ----- |
| **name description remedy severity**: “1.0” \- “10.0” (string) **location**: required for CODE | **referenceIds**: array of CVE, GHSA and other IDs **cwes**: array of CWEs in the form “CWE-xxxx” **location**: e.g. source file or asset name **publishedDateTime**: “YYYY:MM:DD HH:MM:SS” (defaults to current date-time) **details**: JSON object with any additional details. They will be captured and displayed. |

 

**Tag**

# Applications and Environments Endpoints {#applications-and-environments-endpoints}

## Applications/Environments List {#applications/environments-list}

In order to obtain the list of applications and environments you can use the following request:

**GET /v1/applications**

### **Query Parameters**

Request page parameters:

`?pageNumber=<0-based-page>&pageSize=<page-size>`

### **Response**

A successful request would return a JSON document with the following format:

`{`  
   `"content":[ Application objects ],`  
   `"last":"boolean",`  
   `"first":"boolean",`  
   `"pageSize":"number",`  
   `"pageNumber":"number",`  
   `"pageNumberOfElements":"number",`  
   `"totalPages":"number",`  
   `"totalElements":"number"`  
`}`

#### **Application Object**

The structure of the application object in the response is as follows:

`{`  
     	`"id":"uuid",`  
     	`"organizationId":"uuid",`  
     	`"name":"string",`  
     	`"owner":{`  
        	`"id":"uuid",`  
        	`"email":"string"`  
     		`},`  
     	`"criticality":"number",`  
     	`"value":"number",`  
     	`"risk":"number",`  
     	`"threshold":"number",`  
     	`"aboveThreshold":"boolean",`  
     	`"type":"string",`  
     	`"subType":"string",`  
     	`"responsibleUsers":[ {"id":"uuid", "email":"string"} ],`  
     	`"tags":[ {"key":"string", "value":"string"} ],`  
	`"stats": {... see AppStats object below ...},`  
     	`"default":"boolean"`  
 `}`

In the returned application/environment data:

* **type**: Indicates if the entity is an Application or an Environment  
* **subType**: For Environments only, it indicates if it’s a Cloud or Infra environment. Otherwise it’s null or missing.

#### **AppStats Object**

The structure of the AppStats object in the response is as follows:

`{`  
  `"findings": {`  
    `"open": number,`  
    `"closed": number,`  
    `"openByRisk": {`  
      `"critical": number,`  
      `"high": number,`  
      `"medium": number,`  
      `"low": number,`  
      `"none": number`  
    `}`  
  `},`  
  `"assets": {`  
    `"total": number`  
  `}`  
`}`

## Single Application/Environment {#single-application/environment}

In order to obtain the details of an application or environment you can use the following request:

## Create Application/Environment {#create-application/environment}

To create a new application or environment you can use the following request:

**POST /v1/applications**

### **Parameters**

Requests parameters are sent in the POST body:

`{`  
   `"name":"string",`  
   `"type":"string",`  
   `"subType": "string",`  
   `"threshold":"number",`  
   `"value":"number",`  
   `"criticality":"number",`  
   `"owner":{`  
  	`"id":"uuid",`  
  	`"email":"string"`  
   `},`  
   `"responsibleUsers":[`  
  	`{`  
     	`"id":"uuid",`  
     	`"email":"string"`  
  	`}`  
   `],`  
   `"tags":[`  
  	`{`  
     	`"key":"string",`  
     	`"value":"string"`  
  	`}`  
   `],`  
   `"ticketing": {`  
        `"integrationId": string?,`  
        `"integrationName": string?,`  
        `"projectId": string?,`  
        `"projectName": string,`  
        `"integrationType": string? (e.g. "JIRA")`  
    `},`  
    `"messaging": {`  
        `"integrationId": string?,`  
        `"integrationName": string?,`  
        `"channelId": string?,`  
        `"channelName": string`  
    `}`  
`}`

where:

* **name**: Application name. Required field (3-255 characters long)  
* **type**: Application Type. Required field. Allowed values: `APPLICATION, ENVIRONMENT`  
* **subType**: Required for `ENVIRONMENT` application type. Allowed values: `CLOUD, INFRA`  
* **threshold.** Optional field `(0-1000)`, otherwise inherited from Organization threshold  
* **value**: Optional field `(1000-10000000)`  
* **criticality:** Required field `(1-10)`  
* **owner:** Required object. Either `id` or `email` must be provided  
* **responsibleUsers\[\]:** Optional array of objects. Either `id` or `email` must be provided  
* **tags\[\]**: Optional array of objects. A `key` is optional, `value` is required

### **Response**

A successful request would return a JSON document with the created [Application](#applications/environments-list) object.

Tags can be **removed** from applications and environments by using the following endpoint.

**PATCH /v1/applications/\<application-id\>/tags**

### **Path Parameters**

* **application-id**: This is the internal ID of the application, as returned in the “id” field of the application list request’s response. Must not be the Default Application.. (See [Identifying Applications by Name](#identifying-applications/environments-by-name) for an alternative.)

### **Parameters**

Requests parameters are sent in the PATCH body:

`{`  
   `"action": "delete",`  
   `"tags":[`  
      `{`  
         `"id": "uuid",`  
         `"key": "string",`  
         `"value": "string"`  
      `}`  
   `]`  
`}`

where:

* **action:** Should be “***delete***”.  
* **tags\[\]:** Array of objects. `id` is optional, `key` is optional, `value` is required. If `id` is specified key/value would be ignored.

### 

### **Response**

A successful response will return the **204** HTTP Status Code without a response body. If no tags are matched for removal the request will return **404** Not Found.

## **Add Deployment Link to an Application** {#add-deployment-link-to-an-application}

With the following endpoint API clients can add deployment links to an application. If the application is already deployed, the new link will **replace** the previous one.

**PATCH /v1/applications/\<application-id\>/deploy**

### **Path Parameters**

* **application-id**: This is the internal ID of the application, as returned in the “id” field of the application list request’s response. It must be an **Application ID,** not an Environment's.

### **Parameters**

Requests parameters are sent in the PATCH body:

`{`  
   `"serviceSelector":{`  
   	`"id": "uuid",`  
`"name": "string",`  
`"caseSensitive": boolean,`  
`"tags": [`  
  `{`  
    `"key": "string",`  
    `"value": "string"`  
  `}`  
`],`  
`"matchAssetTags": boolean`  
   `}`  
`}`

where **serviceSelector** contains:

* **id:** Optional**.** Phoenix identifier of the service where the application would be deployed. Either `id` or `name` must be provided and they must already exist in the organisation.  
* **name**: Optional. The name of the service where the application would be deployed. If multiple services match the name, the first one would be used.  
* **caseSensitive**: Optional. Whether “*name*” above should be searched in a case sensitive way. Defaults to **true**.  
* **tags**: Optional. A list of tags that would be used to match the service to deploy the application onto. Selected services need to match at least ONE of the tags, and only the first matching service would be used.  
* **matchAssetTags**: Optional. Whether to match services by the tags in their **assets**, as well as the service’s own tags. The default value is ***true***.

Fields within serviceSelector offer different ways of identifying services within Phoenix. At least one needs to be present, and if more than one are provided **only** the first one in this order would be used: id, name, tags.

### **Response**

A successful request would return a JSON document with the updated [Application](#applications/environments-list) object.

If no service is found the response status is ***404** Not Found*.

## **Link Repository to an App/Env** {#link-repository-to-an-app/env}

This request can be used to add a “**repository rule**” to an application or environment. It will add a new rule to an existing component, or create a new component for the rule, depending on the parameters. This rule associates any asset with a “*repository*” attribute that matches the given name.

**POST /v1/applications/\<application-id\>/repository**

### **Path Parameters**

* **application-id**: This is the internal ID of the application, as returned in the “id” field of the application list request’s response. Must not be the **Default Application**.

### **Parameters**

Requests parameters are sent in the POST body:

`{`  
  `"repository": "string",`  
  `"search": "string",`  
  `"component": {`  
    `"id": "uuid",`  
    `"name": "string",`  
    `"criticality": number,`  
    `"tags": [`  
      `{`  
    	  `"key": "string",`  
    	  `"value": "string"`  
      `}`  
    `]`  
  `}`  
`}`

where:

* **repository:** Repository name. Required field. It’s the name of the repository for the rule. (It will be used as part of the component name to create a new component if **componentName** is not provided.)  
* **search**: Optional. It defines a search substring to match on the asset IDs while selecting assets from the matching *repository*. It can be used to select a subset of assets within the repository.  
* **component**: Optional. Defines which component the repository (rule) should be added to within the application. If not present a new component would be created using the repository name.  
  * **name:** Custom name to create a new component. Optional field. The name must be unique in the application. Required, unless “id” is present.  
  * **id:** Provide specific existing component ID to link the rule to an existing component. Optional field. Must not be the **Default Component**. Required if “name” is not present.  
  * **criticality**: Optional. A value between 1 and 10 to define the criticality of the component; it overrides the application’s criticality.  
  * **tags**: a list of key/value tags (key is optional) to add to the new or existing component.

If “***component***” is provided, the repository must not exist inside that component. Otherwise, a new component will be created and the repository must not exist inside the application.

### **Response**

A successful request would return a JSON document with the updated [Application](#applications/environments-list) object.

## **Identifying Applications/Environments by Name** {#identifying-applications/environments-by-name}

The endpoints above that require a **\<application-id\>** parameter in the URL have an alternative version that uses the team’s name instead.

To use the alternative version, use the same URL but removing the ***\<application-id\>*** segment, and add a team selector to the body of the request.

`{`  
  `...`  
     
  `"applicationSelector": {`  
  	`"name": "string",`  
	`"caseSensitive": boolean (optional; defaults to true)`  
  `}`  
`}`

In this case the platform will search the application/environment by name, optionally using a case insensitive matching.

# Asset Association Rules API Endpoints {#asset-association-rules-api-endpoints}

The following endpoints are used to manage the set of asset association rules that map assets to Components and Services.

## Add Asset Association Rules {#add-asset-association-rules}

Add rule to Component/Service to associate assets to Components are Services. The endpoint is:

**POST /v1/components/rules**

### **Parameters**

Requests parameters are sent in the POST body:

`{`  
  `"selector": {`  
	`"applicationSelector": {`  
  	  `"id": "string",`  
  	  `"name": "string",`  
  	  `"caseSensitive": true`  
	`},`  
	`"componentSelector": {`  
  	  `"name": "string",`  
  	  `"caseSensitive": true`  
	`}`  
  `},`  
  `"rules": [`  
    `{`  
      `"name": "string",`  
      `"filter": {`  
        `"ids": ["uuid"],`  
        `"keyLike": "string",`  
        `"tags": [{`  
            `"key": "string",`  
            `"value": "string"`  
      	  `}]`  
	`// CLOUD =============`  
        `"providerAccountId": ["string"],`  
        `"providerAccountName": ["string"],`  
        `"resourceGroup": [“string”],`  
	`// INFRA =============`  
        `"assetType": "CONTAINER" | "INFRA",`  
        `"cidr": “cidr”,`  
        `"hostnames": ["string"],`  
        `"osNames": ["string"],`  
        `"netbios": ["string"]`  
	`// APPSEC =============`  
        `"assetType": "REPOSITORY" | ”SOURCE_CODE" | "BUILD" | "WEBSITE_API",`  
        `"cidr": "cidr",`  
        `"fqdn": ["string"],`  
        `"repository": ["string"]`  
      `}`  
    `}`  
  `]`  
`}`

where:

* **applicationSelector**: Required. Used to identify the Environment where the Service is located.  
* **componentSelector**: Required.  Used to identify the Service where the new rule(s) should be defined.  
* **rules:** Required. List of rules defined as:  
  * **name**: The rule’s name  
  * **filter**: A list of filters that define the rule \- for now only “tags” filter is available.  
    * **ids**: Array of asset IDs (UUIDs). If provided, these assets \- and only these \- are selected by the rule.  
    * **keyLike**: Case sensitive search substring matched against the assets key. It should be surrounded by “\*” characters: e.g. “\*prod\*”.  
    * **tags**: Array of objects. A `key` is optional, `value` is required.

For Cloud environments, the filter object can include:

* **providerAccountId**: The cloud provider’s ID of the account or subscription where the assets belong.  
* **providerAccountName**: The friendly name of the cloud provider’s account or subscription.  
* **resourceGroup**: The name of the resource group where the cloud asset belongs \- if applicable.

For Infra environments, the filter object can include:

* **assetType**: Possible values are “INFRA” and “CONTAINER”. If missing, all types would be included.  
* **cidr**: A range of IP addresses defined as a valid CIDR value  
* **hostnames**: List of hostnames to match  
* **osNames**: List of operating system names to match  
* **netbios**: List of NetBIOS names to match

For applications, the filter object can include:

* **assetType**: Possible values are “REPOSITORY”, “SOURCE\_CODE”, “BUILD” and “WEBSITE\_API”. If missing, all types would be included.  
* **cidr**: A range of IP addresses defined as a valid CIDR value  
* **fqdn**: List of domain names to match.  
* **repository**: List of repository names to match. Applies to all asset types except WEBSITE\_API.

**Important**: This endpoint will prevent duplication of rules inside the same Component or Service. In order to do this, the rules are compared based on their definition (filters), not their name.

### **Response**

A successful request would return an HTTP code **201 Created**, with the body of the response containing an indication of the number of rules added.

If all the rules are already present in the Component/Service, the platform would respond with HTTP code **409 Conflict**.

## **Create Team** {#create-team}

**POST /v1/teams**

### **Parameters**

Requests parameters are sent in the POST body:

    `"name": "string",`  
    `"type": "string"`  
`}`

where:

* **name**: Required field. Name of the team. Must be unique in the organisation  
* **type**: Required field. Team type. Allowed values: `GENERAL, SECURITY`

### **Response**

`}`

 

## **Add users to a Team** {#add-users-to-a-team}

This request adds new team members to a Team.

**PUT /v1/teams/\<team-id\>/users**

### **Path Parameters**

* **team-id**: This is the internal ID of the team, as returned in the “id” field of the team list request’s response. (See [Identifying Teams by Name](#identifying-teams-by-name) for an alternative.)

### **Parameters**

Requests parameters are sent in the POST body:

`{`  
   `"users":[`  
      `{`  
         `"id": "uuid",`  
         `"email":"string"`  
      `}`  
   `],`  
   `"autoCreateUsers": boolean`  
`}`

where

* **users\[\]:** Array of objects. Either `id` or `email` must be provided.  
* **autoCreateUsers**: Optional boolean; defaults to “false”. When set to “**true**”, if users are identified by email and they are not present in the platform already they will be auto-created (with Org User role). Otherwise, the request will return code 400 “Invalid user email” for missing users.

### **Response**

A successful response will return the **200** HTTP Status Code without a response body.

If *all* users in the *users\[\]* array are already members of the team the request will return a **409** HTTP status code. No changes will be made to the team.

If *any* *users\[\].id* or *users\[\].email* (without aoutCreateUsers enabled) value is not found in the platform, the request will return **400** HTTP status code.

## **Auto-link Apps/Envs to the Team by tags** {#auto-link-apps/envs-to-the-team-by-tags}

With this endpoint clients can configure the auto-link tags used to link applications and environments to a team.

**POST /v1/teams/\<team-id\>/applications/auto-link/tags**

### **Path Parameters**

* **team-id**: This is the internal ID of the team, as returned in the “id” field of the team list request’s response. (See [Identifying Teams by Name](#identifying-teams-by-name) for an alternative.)

### **Parameters**

Requests parameters are sent in the POST body:

`{`  
   `"match": "string",`  
   `"tags":[`  
      `{`  
         `"id": "uuid",`  
         `"key": "string",`  
         `"value": "string"`  
      `}`  
   `]`  
`}`

where:

* **match:** Is a tag match expression. Optional field. Allowed values: `ANY, ALL`. If not provided, and if the team doesn’t have an auto-link rule, `ANY` is used. If not provided, and if the team has an existing auto-link rule, the existing rule's expression will be used.  
* **tags\[\]:** Array of objects. `id` is optional, `key` is optional, `value` is required.

### **Response**

A successful response will return the **200** HTTP Status Code without a response body.

If the *match* mode is not provided, or hasn’t changed, and all *tags\[\]* are already in the team’s configuration, the request will return **409** HTTP status code.

## **Remove applications auto-link tags** {#remove-applications-auto-link-tags}

This request **removes** specific tags previously configured in the team for auto-linking to Apps/Envs. After invoking this request on a team the specified tag(s) will be removed from the team’s auto-linking configuration.

**PATCH /v1/teams/\<team-id\>/applications/auto-link/tags**

### **Path Parameters**

* **team-id**: This is the internal ID of the team, as returned in the “id” field of the team list request’s response. (See [Identifying Teams by Name](#identifying-teams-by-name) for an alternative.)

### **Parameters**

Requests parameters are sent in the PATCH body:

`{`  
   `"action": "delete",`  
   `"tags":[`  
      `{`  
         `"id": "uuid",`  
         `"key": "string",`  
         `"value": "string"`  
      `}`  
   `]`  
`}`

where:

* **action:** Should be “***delete***”.  
* **tags\[\]:** Array of objects. `id` is optional, `key` is optional, `value` is required. If `id` is specified key/value would be ignored.

### **Response**

A successful response will return the **204** HTTP Status Code without a response body.

## **Remove auto-link applications to the team by tags** {#remove-auto-link-applications-to-the-team-by-tags}

This request **removes** any tags previously configured in the team for auto-linking to Apps/Envs. After invoking this request on a team it will not have any auto-linking by tags configured.

### **Path Parameters**

## **Enable auto-linking Apps/Envs to a Team by team Members** {#enable-auto-linking-apps/envs-to-a-team-by-team-members}

This will auto-link apps/envs to the team if team members are set as responsible users in the application.

### **Response**

A successful response will return the **200** HTTP Status Code without a response body.

## **Identifying Teams by Name** {#identifying-teams-by-name}

The endpoints above that require a **\<team-id\>** parameter in the URL have an alternative version that uses the team’s name instead.

To use the alternative version, use the same URL but removing the ***\<team-id\>*** segment, and add a team selector to the body of the request.

`{`  
  `...`  
     
  `"teamSelector": {`  
  	`"name": "string",`  
	`"caseSensitive": boolean (optional; defaults to true)`  
  `}`  
`}`

In this case the platform will search the team by name, optionally using a case insensitive matching.

# Users Endpoints {#users-endpoints}

## **List Users** {#list-users}

Provides a list of all users defined within the organisation.

**GET /v1/users**

### **Query Parameters**

Request page parameters (optional, default values 0-100):

`?pageNumber=0&pageSize=100`

### **Response**

A successful request would return a JSON document with the following format (User objects):

`{`  
   `"content":[`  
      `{`  
         `"id":"uuid",`  
         `"email":"string",`  
         `"firstName":"string",`  
         `"lastName":"string",`  
         `"active":"boolean",`  
         `"role":"string"`  
      `}`  
   `],`  
   `"last":"boolean",`  
   `"first":"boolean",`  
   `"pageSize":"number",`  
   `"pageNumber":"number",`  
   `"pageNumberOfElements":"number",`  
   `"totalPages":"number",`  
   `"totalElements":"number"`

`}`

## **Create User** {#create-user}

Creates a new user within the organisation and sends the welcome and one-time-password emails to the provided address. This action is equivalent to creating a user through the Phoenix Security user interface.

**POST /v1/users**

### **Parameters**

Requests parameters are sent in the POST body:

`{`  
    `"email": "string",`  
    `"firstName": "string",`  
    `"lastName": "string",`  
    `"role": "string"`

`}`

Where:

* **email:** User’s email. Required field. Must be unique in the organisation.  
* **firstName:** User’s first name. Required field  
* **lastName:** User’s last name. Required field  
* **role:** User’s role. Required field. Allowed values: `ORG_ADMIN, ORG_APP_ADMIN, ORG_USER, ORG_ADMIN_LITE, ORG_SEC_ADMIN, ORG_SEC_DEV`

 

### **Response**

A successful request would return an **200** HTTP status code and a JSON document with the following format (User object):

`{`  
   `"id":"uuid",`  
   `"email":"string",`  
   `"firstName":"string",`  
   `"lastName":"string",`  
   `"active":"boolean",`  
   `"role":"string"`  
`}`

If a user already exists with the same ***email*** provided in the request, the response will be a **409** HTTP status code.
